üîπ 1. What is a Port?
In computer networking, a port is a logical communication endpoint that helps identify specific processes or services on a device.

When two systems communicate over a network:
The IP address identifies which system to reach.
The port number identifies which service or process on that system to communicate with.

üè† Simple Analogy
Imagine your computer as a big apartment building:
The IP address is the building‚Äôs address.
The ports are different doors to various rooms in that building.
Each door (port) leads to a different service:
Door 22 ‚Üí SSH room
Door 80 ‚Üí Web browsing room
Door 25 ‚Üí Email room
So when someone wants to reach your computer for a specific service, they must know which door (port) to use.

üîπ 2. How Ports Work
When two computers talk over a network:
They connect using IP address (to find each other).
They use a port number (to know which service or program to talk to).

For example:
ssh user@192.168.1.10
Here:
192.168.1.10 ‚Üí IP address (which computer to contact)
Port 22 (default for SSH) ‚Üí which service to use on that computer
So, SSH uses port 22 by default.

üîπ 3. Port Number Range
Every computer has 65,536 ports ‚Äî numbered from 0 to 65535.
They‚Äôre divided into 3 categories:
| Range             | Name                        | Used For                                           |
| ----------------- | --------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------- |
| **0 ‚Äì 1023**      | **Well-known ports**        | Common services (used by system programs)          |
| **1024 ‚Äì 49151**  | **Registered ports**        | Used by software and applications                  |
| **49152 ‚Äì 65535** | **Dynamic / Private ports** | Temporary ports used by clients during connections |


üîπ 4. Common Port Numbers You Should Know
| Service   | Protocol | Port     | Description                              |
| --------- | -------- | -------- | ---------------------------------------- |
| **SSH**   | TCP      | **22**   | Secure remote login to Linux servers     |
| **FTP**   | TCP      | **21**   | File Transfer Protocol                   |
| **HTTP**  | TCP      | **80**   | Normal web browsing (insecure)           |
| **HTTPS** | TCP      | **443**  | Secure web browsing                      |
| **SMTP**  | TCP      | **25**   | Sending emails                           |
| **DNS**   | UDP      | **53**   | Converting website names to IP addresses |
| **MySQL** | TCP      | **3306** | Database connections                     |
| **RDP**   | TCP      | **3389** | Remote Desktop (Windows)                 |
| **NTP**   | UDP      | **123**  | Time synchronization                     |
| **POP3**  | TCP      | **110**  | Receiving emails (older method)          |

